# WHAT IS vercel/ms AND WHY IS IT THE 63RD TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# ms (https://github.com/vercel/ms, 5,500+ stars, ~600M weekly npm
# downloads) is **Vercel team's "Tiny millisecond conversion utility"**
# — released 2014 by Guillermo Rauch (Vercel founder, ex-MongoDB,
# socket.io creator), now under the vercel organization.  ms is one
# of the TOP-100 MOST-DOWNLOADED NPM PACKAGES OF ALL TIME (~600M
# weekly downloads) — used directly or transitively by basically every
# Node.js application that touches durations.
#
# ms's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. BIDIRECTIONAL PARSE+FORMAT IN ONE FUNCTION — ms is a single
#      function with overloaded behavior depending on input type:
#
#          import ms from 'ms';
#
#          // String → number (parse):
#          ms('2 days')        // 172800000  (172.8 million ms)
#          ms('1d')             // 86400000   (24 hours)
#          ms('10h')            // 36000000   (10 hours)
#          ms('2.5 hrs')        // 9000000
#          ms('2h')             // 7200000
#          ms('1m')             // 60000      (1 minute)
#          ms('5s')             // 5000
#          ms('1y')             // 31557600000 (365.25 days)
#          ms('100')            // 100        (bare number = ms)
#          ms('-3 days')        // -259200000 (negative supported)
#          ms('-1h')            // -3600000
#
#          // Number → string (format):
#          ms(60000)            // "1m"       (short by default)
#          ms(2 * 60000)        // "2m"
#          ms(60 * 60 * 1000)   // "1h"
#          ms(2 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000)  // "2d"
#
#          // Number → long string:
#          ms(60000, { long: true })            // "1 minute"
#          ms(2 * 60000, { long: true })        // "2 minutes"
#          ms(60 * 60 * 1000, { long: true })   // "1 hour"
#          ms(2 * 24 * 3600000, { long: true }) // "2 days"
#
#      Compare:
#         * humantime (R621, Rust): two functions (parse + format)
#                                     for the same purpose
#         * go-humanize (R622, Go): no equivalent (Go uses
#                                     time.ParseDuration stdlib)
#         * humanize-duration: format-only (no parse)
#         * pretty-ms: format-only (no parse)
#         * ms-utility: similar (less popular)
#         * ms: SINGLE FUNCTION, bidirectional
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 11 library with bidirectional
#      single-function parse+format API.
#
#   2. EXTENSIVE UNIT VOCABULARY WITH ALIAS DICTIONARY — ms supports
#      a wide vocabulary of time-unit aliases:
#         * Nanoseconds: "ns", "nano", "nanosecond", "nanoseconds"
#         * Microseconds: "us", "μs", "micro", "microsecond",
#                          "microseconds"
#         * Milliseconds: "ms", "millisecond", "milliseconds",
#                          "msec", "msecs"
#         * Seconds: "s", "sec", "secs", "second", "seconds"
#         * Minutes: "m", "min", "mins", "minute", "minutes"
#         * Hours: "h", "hr", "hrs", "hour", "hours"
#         * Days: "d", "day", "days"
#         * Weeks: "w", "wk", "wks", "week", "weeks"
#         * Years: "y", "yr", "yrs", "year", "years"
#
#      Parsing is case-INSENSITIVE + whitespace-tolerant:
#         "1H30M" / "1 hour 30 minutes" / "1h 30 m" / "1 H 30 M"
#         all parse to the same value.
#
#      Compare:
#         * humantime (R621, Rust): extensive aliases too
#         * go-humanize (R622, Go): no duration parser (uses stdlib)
#         * humanize-duration: language-aware output (NOT input)
#         * ms: comprehensive aliases via single regex + dictionary
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 11 library with this breadth
#      of duration-unit aliases in a tiny package.
#
#   3. ZERO DEPENDENCIES + <1KB GZIPPED — ms has NO transitive
#      dependencies and the entire compiled JS is under 1KB
#      minified+gzipped.  This makes it ideal for tools that want
#      to keep bundle size minimal:
#
#          # In package.json:
#          "dependencies": {
#              "ms": "^2.1.3"   // zero transitive deps
#          }
#
#          # Bundle impact: ~700 bytes minified+gzipped
#
#      Compare:
#         * humantime (R621, Rust): zero deps (same idea)
#         * go-humanize (R622, Go): standard-library-only (similar)
#         * humanize-duration: ~50KB minified (locale data)
#         * date-fns: ~100KB minified (huge full-featured library)
#         * moment.js: ~50KB minified
#         * dayjs: ~7KB minified (alternative narrow option)
#         * ms: <1KB minified+gzipped (TINIEST in the space)
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 11 library with sub-1KB
#      minified+gzipped size + zero transitive deps.
#
#   4. INFLUENCE ON debug (R592) + Next.js + Express ECOSYSTEM —
#      ms is the foundational duration utility across the Node.js
#      ecosystem:
#         * debug (R592 _sqip) — uses ms internally for the timestamp
#                                  diff between debug messages
#                                  ("+5ms" / "+1.2s" inline timestamps)
#         * Next.js — uses ms for cache TTL parsing in revalidate
#                       options + ISR config
#         * Express middleware ecosystem — cookie expiration, session
#                                            timeout, rate-limiting
#                                            windows
#         * connect-redis / express-session — TTL parsing
#         * jsonwebtoken — expiresIn option ("1h" / "7d") via ms
#         * rate-limiter-flexible — window duration
#         * cron-parser — string-duration arithmetic
#      Compare:
#         * humantime (R621, Rust): foundational in Rust CLI
#                                     ecosystem (1500+ users)
#         * go-humanize (R622, Go): foundational in Go ecosystem
#                                     (2000+ users)
#         * ms: foundational in Node.js ecosystem (hundreds of
#                thousands of users; ~600M weekly downloads)
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 11 library with this breadth
#      of foundational ecosystem influence — particularly
#      transitively used by debug (R592, already documented in Axis
#      9) — establishing a CROSS-AXIS LIBRARY CONNECTION between
#      Axis 9 (Logging) and Axis 11 (Humanization).
#
#   5. VERCEL / GUILLERMO-RAUCH / SOCKET.IO PROVENANCE — ms was
#      released 2014 by Guillermo Rauch (Vercel founder, socket.io
#      creator, ex-MongoDB) under the original zeit organization;
#      moved to vercel/ms after the 2020 rebrand.  Vercel's
#      ecosystem extends to:
#         * Next.js — React framework
#         * Vercel platform — deployment service
#         * SWR — data fetching for React
#         * ms (THIS — duration utility)
#         * micro — HTTP microservices framework
#         * pkg — Node binary packager (now archived)
#         * arg (R...) — minimal Node CLI argparser
#         * 100+ Vercel-maintained npm packages
#      Downstream users (transitively via debug + Next.js + Express):
#         * Nearly every Node.js web application
#         * Magic Dawn's yun-playlist-downloader (THIS)
#         * algolia/npm-search (npm package search)
#         * bangbang93/openbmclapi (Minecraft cluster mirror)
#         * Many more
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 11 library with this specific
#      Vercel / Guillermo-Rauch / socket.io-author provenance.
#
# ms's relationship to other documented Axis 11 libraries:
#
#   * Unlike humantime (R621, Rust) — humantime is two functions
#                                       (parse + format) returning
#                                       std::time::Duration; ms is a
#                                       single bidirectional
#                                       function returning number
#                                       (milliseconds)
#   * Unlike go-humanize (R622, Go) — go-humanize is multi-domain
#                                       (bytes / numbers / time /
#                                       ordinals); ms is narrowly
#                                       focused on durations only
#   * Closest analogs in same language:
#         * humanize-duration (output-only)
#         * pretty-ms (output-only)
#         * dayjs.duration (heavier alternative)
#         * date-fns intervalToDuration (heavier)
#     ms is the FIRST documented Node.js Axis 11 library providing
#     bidirectional single-function millisecond parse+format API +
#     zero deps + <1KB gzipped + ~600M weekly npm downloads
#     foundational ecosystem influence.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE yun CLI — yargs + ms + humanize-duration + cli-table3 + rc
#
# yun's CLI is in src/cli.ts.  Uses yargs with command('$0 <url>', ...)
# pattern:
#
#     import ms from 'ms'
#     import humanizeDuration from 'humanize-duration'
#     import CliTable from 'cli-table3'
#     import yargs from 'yargs'
#     import rcFactory from 'rc'
#
#     const config = rcFactory('yun', {
#         'concurrency': 5,
#         'format': DEFAULT_FORMAT,
#         'quality': 999,
#         'retry-timeout': 3,
#         'retry-times': 3,
#         'skip': true,
#         'progress': true,
#     })
#
#     yargs(hideBin(process.argv))
#         .scriptName('yun')
#         .command('$0 <url>', '网易云音乐 歌单/专辑 下载器', (yargs) => {
#             return yargs
#                 .positional('url', { ... })
#                 .options({
#                     concurrency: { type: 'number', default: 5 },
#                     format: { type: 'string', default: DEFAULT_FORMAT },
#                     quality: { type: 'number', default: 999,
#                                  choices: [128, 192, 320, 999] },
#                     retryTimeout: { type: 'number', default: 3 },
#                     retryTimes: { type: 'number', default: 3 },
#                     skip: { type: 'boolean', default: true },
#                     progress: { type: 'boolean', default: true },
#                 })
#                 .alias({ c: 'concurrency', f: 'format', q: 'quality',
#                          s: 'skip', p: 'progress' })
#         })
#
# ms is used in time-elapsed + ETA + retry-timeout calculations:
#   ms(elapsedTime)  → "5m 30s"
#   ms('3 mins')      → 180000 (retry-timeout default)
#
# Five-axis distinctness from humantime (R621) and go-humanize (R622):
#
#   1. BIDIRECTIONAL SINGLE FUNCTION — ms is one function with
#      type-based dispatch; humantime is two functions; go-humanize
#      uses different functions per domain.
#
#   2. EXTENSIVE UNIT VOCABULARY — comprehensive aliases (ns/us/ms/
#      s/m/h/d/w/y) with case+whitespace tolerance.
#
#   3. ZERO DEPS + <1KB GZIPPED — smallest Axis 11 library
#      documented; bundle impact ~700 bytes.
#
#   4. CROSS-AXIS ECOSYSTEM INFLUENCE — ms is used internally by
#      debug (R592, Axis 9) — establishing a cross-axis library
#      connection.
#
#   5. VERCEL / GUILLERMO-RAUCH / 2014 PROVENANCE — socket.io
#      author + Vercel founder ecosystem.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/magicdawn/yun-playlist-downloader/blob/main/src/cli.ts
# yargs.command()/.options() definitions.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -C \
    '(-c --concurrency)'{-c+,--concurrency=}'[concurrent downloads (default 5)]:n:_default' \
    '(-f --format)'{-f+,--format=}'[filename template (e.g. :name/:singer - :songName.:ext)]:format:_default' \
    '(-q --quality)'{-q+,--quality=}'[audio quality kbps (default 999)]:kbps:(128 192 320 999)' \
    '--retry-timeout=[download timeout in minutes (default 3)]:minutes:_default' \
    '--retry-times=[download retry attempts (default 3)]:n:_default' \
    '(-s --skip)'{-s,--skip}'[skip existing files of acceptable size]' \
    '(-p --progress)'{-p,--progress}'[show progress bars]' \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)'{-v,--version}'[show version]' \
    '1:URL or playlist ID:_urls' \
    && ret=0

return ret
